  "prompt": "What are the good ways to calculate percentage of equity giving to venture capital when a startup gets funded?",
  "response": "When determining the percentage of equity to give to venture capital (VC) investors, consider these key approaches:\n\n1. Traditional Ownership Benchmarks\n- Seed Round: 10-25% equity\n- Series A: 15-30% equity\n- Series B: 10-25% equity\n\n2. Calculation Methods\n- Pre-money valuation\n- Post-money valuation\n- Amount invested vs. company's total value\n\n3. Factors Influencing Equity Percentage\n- Company stage\n- Market potential\n- Team experience\n- Growth projections\n- Investor's reputation\n- Funding amount\n\n4. Common Dilution Frameworks\n- First round: 15-25%\n- Subsequent rounds: 10-20%\n- Total dilution across funding rounds: 60-80%\n\n5. Best Practices\n- Maintain founder control (>50%)\n- Negotiate fair terms\n- Consider investor value beyond money\n- Use cap table modeling\n- Understand long-term implications\n\n6. Alternative Approaches\n- SAFE notes\n- Convertible notes\n- Equity with performance triggers\n\n7. Professional Advice\n- Consult startup lawyers\n- Use financial advisors\n- Network with experienced entrepreneurs\n\nEach startup's situation is unique, so careful analysis and negotiation are crucial.",
